Proposed by {{ill|Tetsuo Yamaori|ja|山折哲雄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a scholar of religious studies, aiming to revive the spirit of unity and harmony between Shinto and Buddhism (Shinbutsu-shūgō) that existed before the Meiji Restoration, the '''Shinbutsu Reijō Association''' was established by 125 shrines and temples, mainly from Kinki, on March 2, 2008 (Heisei 20). The first chairman was {{ill|Kōsei Morimoto|ja|森本公誠|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a senior priest of {{ill|Tōdai-ji|ja|東大寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>[http://www.chugainippoh.co.jp/NEWWEB/n-news/08/news0803/news080304/news080304_01.html Shinbutsu Reijō Association, 125 shrines and temples mainly from Kinki] (Chugai Nippō, March 4, 2008)</ref> Later expanded to 151 shrines and temples, the inaugural ceremony was held at Ise Grand Shrine on September 8, 2008.<ref>[http://chubu.yomiuri.co.jp/news_kan/kan080909_7.htm 151 shrines and temples worship at Ise Grand Shrine] (Yomiuri Shimbun, September 9, 2008)</ref> As of September 8, 2018, with the addition of Niukawakami Shrine Shimo-sha and Gangō-ji, it became 152 shrines and temples besides Ise Grand Shrine (Naikū and Gekū).
== List of Sacred Sites == {| class="wikitable" ! No. !! Regional No. !! Shrine/Temple !! Location !! Remarks |- style="background-color:#ddf" ! | colspan="4" | '''Ise: Path of Shinto-Buddhist Unity''' |- ! | Special || {{ill|Kōtai Jingū|ja|皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Ise City|ja|伊勢市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Nijūnisha|ja|二十二社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |- ! | Special || {{ill|Toyouke Daijingu|ja|豊受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Ise City|ja|伊勢市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Nijūnisha|ja|二十二社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |- style="background-color:#ddf" ! | colspan="4" | '''Wakayama: Path of Purity''' |- !1 | Wakayama 1 || {{ill|Kumano Hayatama Taisha|ja|熊野速玉大社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Shingū City|ja|新宮市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || |- !2 | Wakayama 2 || {{ill|Seiganto-ji|ja|青岸渡寺|1=Seiganto-ji|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Nachikatsuura, Higashimuro|ja|那智勝浦町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Saigoku 33 Kannon|ja|西国三十三所|1=Saigoku Kannon Pilgrimage|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |- [... continued for all listed shrines and temples in similar fashion ...] |- !150 | Shiga 18 || {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || {{ill|Ōtsu City|ja|大津市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} || Headquarters of {{ill|Tendai|ja|天台宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|New Saigoku 33 Kannon|ja|新西国三十三箇所|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |}
== Goshuinchō (Pilgrimage Stamp Book) == An official {{ill|Goshuinchō|ja|朱印帳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is available for 2,700 yen (as of Reiwa 5 [2023]).<ref>[http://shinbutsureijou.net/shuincho.html Pilgrimage Stamp Book - Shinbutsu Reijō Association]</ref> However, some shrines and temples do not distribute it. It is also not available at the starting point, Ise Grand Shrine. Previously, it was distributed at the Jingū Kaikan near Naikū, but currently, it is no longer available. Since September 8, Heisei 30 (2018), two new shrines and temples were added, making the old Goshuinchō insufficient. As a relief measure, paper stamps are available at these newly joined locations. The current Goshuinchō has the names of shrines and temples pre-printed.
